## Visual & Design Direction

### Current state
The site currently uses a Shopify theme/template. Carla (founder) has historically built websites with front-end developers and has found the template approach limiting. Her background includes building websites at Everlane and other design-forward brands.

### What works
- **The hero section** — the photography alone communicates "this is not a typical DTC matcha company." It sets the right tone immediately
- **Product imagery and packaging** — feels high-end and fashion-forward
- **The ticker/marquee element** — adds energy and movement

### What doesn't work
- Sections that follow a predictable **"eyebrow text → headline → body copy → image block"** pattern feel too template-like and rudimentary
- Centered text blocks with image blocks underneath — lacks integration between typography and visuals
- The layout "loses its luster" in the mid-page sections — everything starts to feel samey
- Overall impression: the site looks like something from the **early 2010s**, not where web design is today

### What she wants
- **Typography and imagery integrated together**, not as separate blocks
- **Interactive elements**: scroll-triggered animations, stacking effects, elements that catch your eye as you move through the page
- **Non-standard layouts** that break out of the typical grid/template patterns
- The site should feel more like a **fashion/lifestyle editorial** than a standard e-commerce site
- Think: the way Seed, AG1, or other elevated DTC brands handle their product pages — interactive cards, animations, considered motion design

### Design inspiration references
- **Seed** (seed.com) — interactive product cards, stacking animations, elevated design treatment
- **AG1** (drinkag1.com) — interactive elements, premium feel
- **Shopify Supply Store** — the socks page with product rotation/3D-like motion

### The core design philosophy
The website should feel like you've entered a **curated brand world**, not landed on an e-commerce template. Every section should feel intentional, considered, and slightly unexpected. If it looks like a theme, it's not right.

